title.narrative: 4.2.MOTHER/CHILD FRIENDLY HEALTH SERVICE

description.narrative: 4.2 Increased capacity of the health services to reach all women (especially pregnant women), and infants to provide antenatal care, including EMTCT, nutrition supplementation and counseling, to support their healthy development, which contributes to Child Health, Early Childhood Development, Hiv Prevention, Immunization, Infant And Young Child Feeding, Maternal And Newborn Health, Pmtct And Infant Male Circumcision, Prevention Of Stunting And Other Forms Of Malnutrition, Treatment Of Severe Acute Malnutrition. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By the end of 2019, women, girls and boys, particularly those in rural indigenous areas, access comprehensive package for health, nutrition and Water, Sanitation, and Hygiene (WASH), to guarantee the healthy growth and development, in particular during the child's first 1,000 days (from conception to 2 years of age), and to prevent and reduce chronic malnutrition and morbidity/ mortality.

description.narrative: UNICEF continued to support and promote breastfeeding, supporting the Breastfeeding-Friendly Services Initiative under the National Policy on Hospital Nutrition of Children in 41 hospitals. Specifically, UNICEF directly supported the initiative in 13 centres for continuous assistance and 2 centres for mother and child care.In spite of the continuing COVID-19 pandemic, UNICEF supported the evaluation and re-certification of 10 hospitals as “Breastfeeding-Friendly Hospitals.” In addition, UNICEF continued supporting the Breastfeeding Friendly Birth Attendants Strategy, training 912 birth attendants and certifying 332 of these. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:27/01/2022
